<article id="post-100" class="post-100 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-conflict category-environment category-forced-migration category-migration category-refugee-studies-centre tag-displacement tag-forced-migration-review tag-human-rights tag-humanitarian-governance tag-insecurity tag-natural-disasters tag-protection">
	<header class="entry-header">
		<h1 class="entry-title">Preventing human displacement</h1>

				<div class="entry-meta">
			<span class="sep">Posted on </span><a href="http://blog.qeh.ox.ac.uk/?p=100" title="1:51 pm" rel="bookmark"><time class="entry-date" datetime="2013-01-30T13:51:35+00:00" pubdate>January 30, 2013</time></a><span class="by-author"> <span class="sep"> by </span> <span class="author vcard"><a class="url fn n" href="http://blog.qeh.ox.ac.uk/?author=2" title="View all posts by blogeditor" rel="author">blogeditor</a></span></span>		</div><!-- .entry-meta -->
			</header><!-- .entry-header -->

	<div class="entry-content">
		<p><em>By <a href="http://www.rsc.ox.ac.uk/people/outreach/maurice-herson">Maurice Herson</a></em></p>
<p><a href="http://www.rsc.ox.ac.uk/people/outreach/maurice-herson"><img class="alignright size-full wp-image-104" style="color: #333333; font-size: 15.555556297302246px; font-style: normal; line-height: 26.666667938232422px; margin-top: 0.4em;" alt="Maurice Herson (RSC)" src="http://blog.qeh.ox.ac.uk/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/maurice-herson-dd1.jpg" width="150" height="200" /></a></p>
<p>&#8216;The effects of displacement can last a lifetime and beyond, damaging the prospects of future generations. We can do more to prevent displacement and the suffering it brings.&#8217; So writes UN Under-Secretary-General for Humanitarian Affairs and Emergency Relief Coordinator, Valerie Amos, in the opening article of the latest issue of <em><a href="http://www.fmreview.org/preventing" target="_blank">Forced Migration Review</a></em> (FMR).<span id="more-100"></span></p>
<p>People know that being displaced brings with it risks and vulnerabilities such as loss of land and of work, homelessness, food insecurity, health risks, loss of access to common resources such as education, and possibly destruction of social networks upon which people depend, particularly during a crisis. Being displaced puts people at a higher risk of being both impoverished and unable to enjoy their human rights. But are there situations in which displacement is not inevitable or its likelihood can be reduced?</p>
<p>Politically, economically, strategically and in purely human terms, preventing displacement is obviously a worthwhile objective – but only so long as it makes the choice not to be displaced both feasible and sensible, and we need to be wary that people are not prevented from being able to move when that is their choice, or indeed a necessity. It is important to preserve the possibility of displacement – and it is also worth remembering that two of the three traditional durable solutions, return and resettlement, both involve further displacement.</p>
<p><a href="http://www.fmreview.org/preventing"><img class="alignleft size-full wp-image-108" alt="FMR41: Preventing Displacement" src="http://blog.qeh.ox.ac.uk/wp-content/uploads/2013/01/preventing-displacement.jpg" width="150" height="212" /></a></p>
<p>Addressing the causes of displacement – such as violent conflict, housing that cannot withstand a natural disaster, or a government that cannot guarantee a sustainable infrastructure – is the focus of some of the articles in this issue of FMR. Others look at how to manage situations that might cause displacement so as to make staying a better option. And yet others look at the legal and institutional context within which all this occurs.</p>
<p>The full issue is online at <a href="http://www.fmreview.org/preventing" target="_blank">www.fmreview.org/preventing</a> in html, pdf and audio formats in English, and in html in French, Spanish and Arabic – and also includes a number of articles about disparate aspects of forced migration.</p>
<p><em><a href="http://www.rsc.ox.ac.uk/people/outreach/maurice-herson">Maurice Herson</a> is Co-editor of <a href="http://www.fmreview.org/">Forced Migration Review</a>. </em><em>FMR is the most widely read publication on forced migration – available in English, French, Spanish and Arabic, and free of charge in print and online. It is the in-house magazine of the <a href="http://www.rsc.ox.ac.uk/">Refugee Studies Centre</a> in the Oxford Department of International Development. T</em><em>hrough FMR, authors from around the world analyse the causes and impacts of displacement; debate policies and programmes; share research findings; reflect the lived experience of displacement; and present examples of good practice and recommendations for policy and action.</em></p>
			</div><!-- .entry-content -->

	<footer class="entry-meta">
